`Effect.all` inside a generator yields a typed tuple; `concurrency: "unbounded"` fires both queries concurrently while the surrounding `Effect.gen` keeps the assembly readable.

```ts
import { Effect, Context, Layer, Data } from "effect";

class CacheError extends Data.TaggedError("CacheError")<{ readonly key: string }> {}

interface Cache {
  readonly warm: (key: string) => Effect.Effect<void, CacheError>;
}
const Cache = Context.GenericTag<Cache>("app/Cache");

export const prefetch = (
  keys: ReadonlyArray<string>
): Effect.Effect<void, CacheError, Cache> =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const cache = yield* Cache;
    yield* Effect.all(keys.map((k) => cache.warm(k)), {
      concurrency: "unbounded",
      discard: true,
    });
  });

export const CacheLive = Layer.succeed(Cache, {
  warm: (_k) => Effect.void,
});
```

`{ concurrency: "unbounded", discard: true }` fans out every warm call in parallel and throws away the `void` results rather than allocating a `ReadonlyArray<void>`.

```ts
